<subSubSection pageId="181" pageNumber="182" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="181.[151,1436,487,1088]" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,992,1016]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="181" pageNumber="182" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
This hermit crab often inhabits tubes of polychaetes or the tube mollusk 
<taxonomicName authority="(Carpenter, 1857)" baseAuthorityName="Carpenter" baseAuthorityYear="1857" class="Gastropoda" family="Vermetidae" genus="Serpulorbis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="181" pageNumber="182" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="squamigerus">
<emphasis box="[1154,1436,992,1016]" italics="true" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">Serpulorbis squamigerus</emphasis>
(Carpenter, 1857)
</taxonomicName>
, or shells of 
<taxonomicName box="[492,663,1028,1052]" class="Scaphopoda" family="Dentaliidae" genus="Dentalium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dentaliida" pageId="181" pageNumber="182" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[492,610,1028,1052]" italics="true" pageId="181" pageNumber="182">Dentalium</emphasis>
spp.
</taxonomicName>
On rare occasions, one will inhabit a coiled shell, but the crab moves awkwardly and will vacate such a shell quickly if offered a suitable tube.
</paragraph>
